        "agitate_body": "You wake up flat. By noon you look four months pregnant. You unbutton your jeans at your desk. You skip dinner plans because you know what's coming. You've googled 'why am I always bloated' so many times your phone autocompletes it. You carry Gas-X like it's chapstick. You eat a salad and bloat. You eat rice and bloat. You eat nothing and somehow still bloat.||You've done the elimination diets. The food sensitivity tests. The $300 functional medicine panels. You've cut dairy, gluten, onions, garlic, beans, cruciferous vegetables — half the foods your mother raised you on. Your gastroenterologist shrugged and said 'IBS.' Your dietitian handed you a FODMAP chart. Nobody asked the obvious question: why can your grandmother eat everything you can't?||The answer is bacterial. Research on 2,084 people across six ethnic groups proved that ethnicity shapes your microbiome more than diet, age, or medical history. When you immigrate — or grow up eating a Western diet your ancestors never touched — the bacterial populations that digest your ancestral foods collapse. You're not intolerant. You're depleted.",
        "cost_headline": "You're spending $150+/month managing a problem that costs $34/month to fix.",
        "cost_body": "Digestive enzymes: $30/month. Specialty groceries to avoid triggers: $80+/month. Gas relief products: $15/month. The gastro copay: $50 per visit. The food sensitivity test that found 27 new 'intolerances': $250. The low-FODMAP cookbook: $34. The anxiety of eating at a restaurant: priceless. Americans spend $4.6 billion annually on digestive products — enzymes, antacids, gas relief, elimination diet foods — treating symptoms of a bacterial problem. Origin costs $1.13 per day. Less than the Gas-X you bought last week.",
        "bridge_headline": "Your gut bacteria are a digestive workforce. Immigration wiped out the crew.",
        "bridge_body": "Published research in Gut confirms that microbiome composition directly determines digestive capacity. L. acidophilus produces lactase — the enzyme that breaks down dairy. L. plantarum ferments complex plant fibers before they can produce gas. These are strains found abundantly in traditional fermented foods across South Asian, East Asian, African, and Latin American diets — foods that disappear within one generation of Westernization. When these bacterial populations collapse, carbohydrates that should break down in the small intestine reach your colon intact and ferment explosively. That fermentation is your bloating. That gas is the sound of bacteria that should be there — but aren't.",
        "citation": "Aziz et al., Gut, 2019 · Tap et al., Cell Host & Microbe, 2017 · Canani et al., World Journal of Gastroenterology, 2016",
        "solution_headline": "Origin doesn't mask your bloating. It rebuilds the bacterial workforce that eliminates it.",
        "solution_body": "L. acidophilus restores lactase production so dairy stops destroying you. L. plantarum breaks down plant fibers before they ferment into gas. B. lactis normalizes intestinal transit so food moves through at the right speed — not too fast, not too slow. L. paracasei calms the immune overreaction that drives IBS-pattern symptoms. MAKTREK Bi-Pass ensures all four strains survive stomach acid alive — because dead bacteria fix nothing. FOS prebiotic feeds them on arrival so they colonize, not just pass through. This isn't symptom management. This is restoration.",
        "lead_headline": "The research paper that explains why your bloating started after immigration.",
        "closing_quote": "Your grandmother ate dal, roti, kimchi, injera, mole — whatever her mother made — and never once googled 'why am I so bloated.' She didn't have better willpower. She had better bacteria. You can get them back."
